## Overview

Certain functions in Technical Analysis (TA) are influenced by the entire range of historical data, resulting in outputs that depend on past values.
These are referred to as _functions with memory_.

* Functions with Memory:
  * Example: EMA (Exponential Moving Average).
  * Relies on the previous value (e.g., the prior dayâ€™s EMA) for calculations.
  * Historical data points have a perpetual influence on all subsequent values.
* Finite-Period Functions:
  * Example: SMA (Simple Moving Average).
  * Calculations are limited to a fixed range of data (e.g., the average of the last N periods).
The following graphic illustrates how three EMAs with identical settings (9 periods) that begin at different times but eventually stabilize and overlap.

<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="unstable" width="800"/>

Functions with memory, such as EMA, may produce _false signals_ during their initial calculations if insufficient historical data is available.
These inconsistencies can introduce noise into trading strategies, affecting their reliability.

## Adjustment
`Core.UnstablePeriodSettings` allows to strip off such initial unstable period.
This allows a TA function to output data only after stabilization, ensuring consistent results regardless of the length of historical data.
In the example here, setting the unstable period to around the 28th price bar would be sufficient.

The general guideline is to strip off as much data as possible. Discarding 100 price bars is typically sufficient for most functions.

By default, there is no unstable period for all TA functions. Users are responsible for determining the appropriate amount of data to exclude for consistent results.

When an unstable period is specified, it is applied globally and affects composite functions (TA functions that use other TA functions).
For instance, setting an unstable period for an `EMA` will also affect the `EMA` calculations within the `MACD` function:

```csharp
Core.UnstablePeriodSettings.Set(Core.UnstableFunc.Ema, 28);
```

To apply the same unstable period across all applicable TA functions in a single call:

```csharp
Core.UnstablePeriodSettings.Set(Core.UnstableFunc.All, 28);
```
